    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Mariscus globosus are flavonoids, saponins, phenolic acids, triterpenoids, and alkaloids, which exhibit remarkable bioactive properties. Flavonoids present in Mariscus globosus are responsible for its antioxidant and anti-inflammatory activities, attributed to their ability to scavenge free radicals and modulate inflammatory pathways. Saponins, a key component of Mariscus globosus, possess antiparasitic, antimicrobial, and anticancer properties, which are associated with their ability to form soap-like compounds that disrupt cell membranes and induce apoptosis in cancer cells. The presence of phenolic acids, including ferulic and caffeic acids, contributes to the plant's antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties, while triterpenoids, such as ursolic and oleanolic acids, exhibit anti-inflammatory and antioxidant activities. Alkaloids, including aucubin and iridoid glycosides, have been shown to possess antimicrobial, anti-inflammatory, and antioxidant properties, underscoring the complex and multifaceted bioactivity of Mariscus globosus.",
